{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01UkCGWvunqMESUqNeo7tXvW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All tests pass. Let me verify the kill_in_sphere `_recount` logic handles the case where dead particles are scattered (not contiguous) properly. The current `_recount` just counts non-zero packed_info in `[:_num_active]`, which is correct even after kills since dead particles get packed_info=0 but stay in place. The `_num_active` becomes the count of non-dead particles in the range, though their indices may have gaps. This is the expected pattern per the PRD notes (compaction is a separate US-029 story).\n\nWait — actually there's a subtle issue. After `_recount`, `_num_active` is reduced, but the live particles may be scattered beyond the new `_num_active` boundary. Let me reconsider this.\n\nLooking at the acceptance criteria again: \"num_active property returns count of non-DEAD particles.\" The issue is that if we have particles at indices [0..9999] and kill some in the middle, `_recount` will set `_num_active` to say 8716, but live particles may exist at indices 8716..9999. Then subsequent spawns would overwrite those live particles.\n\nThe better approach is to track `_num_active` as the high-water mark (the highest index + 1 that was ever allocated), not a count of live particles. The `num_active` property should do the count on-demand if needed. But looking at the acceptance criteria more carefully, it says `num_active` returns count of non-DEAD particles. The `kill_in_sphere` doesn't compact — it just marks as DEAD.\n\nLet me fix this. The `_num_active` should remain the high-water mark, and `num_active` as a property should count non-dead particles."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":295,"cache_read_input_tokens":80425,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":295},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"s